The only two unknowns in Eq. \ref{eq:eq8} are $f_1$ and $f_2$. By equating the real and imaginary parts on both sides of Eq. \ref{eq:eq8}, we can find the values of $f_1$ and $f_2$ required for ideal coupling. Some design considerations and an experimental demonstration for such a two-lens coupling system are given in \cite{Qasim:15}.

Simulations are carried out to test the proposed Fig. \ref{fig:fig1} design for different values of $w_0$, $l$ and $p$ and calculating the efficiencies $\eta$ for the optimal choice of parameters $s$, $f_1$ and $f_2$. The values of the fixed parameters of the system are taken as follows: $\lambda=500$ nm, $f_B=50$ cm, $d_1= 10$ cm, $d=20$ cm, $d_2=10$ cm, and $\sigma = 100$ $\mu$m. Note that in practice, we would use a microscope objective to finally couple light into the SMF. Here, just as a proof-of-concept, without the use of the microscope objective, the value of $\sigma$ is taken to be much higher than the typical value for SMF core radii. It is fairly straightforward to incorporate the use of the microscope objective into our simulations by another application of the Fresnel diffraction integral and use of additional matrices in Eq. \ref{eq:eq7}.

